<li>In New York, <a href="http://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/state/index.asp#SEA2013040504">a personal care aide was charged</a> with attempted theft of $10,200 from an 88-year-old woman in her care. According to the criminal complaint, the aide forged and deposited a check stolen from the woman. </li>
<li><a href="http://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/state/index.asp#SEA2013040501">A New York dentist was jailed</a> and must repay Medicaid nearly $700,000; he illegally paid recruiters to solicit homeless patients from shelters and soup kitchens, fraudulently submitted bills in his son's name and failed to pay taxes. </li>
<li><a href="http://www.justice.gov/usao/txn/PressRelease/2013/APR2013/apr9goodwin_michael_HCF_sen.html">An orthodontist who operated practices in Texas and Indiana was jailed</a> for more than four years and must pay over $3.6 million in a complex Medicaid scam. He scheduled more than 100 patients a day and hired others to perform services that he claimed. Authorities said he directed dental assistants to do comprehensive exams, make diagnoses and plan treatments for patients when he knew that only licensed dentists could render those services.     </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/state/index.asp#SEA2013032101">Another dentist, this one in Hawaii, was convicted of Medicaid fraud</a> and must repay almost $36,000 for submitting claims for dental restorations he did not do, or, while claiming restorations, provided services that were far less costly.   </li>
<li><a href="http://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013040203">A former Richmond, Texas, doctor was convicted</a> of fraud in a $19 million Medicare/Medicaid testing scheme. </li>
<li><a href="http://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013040503">Three were convicted in Dallas</a> in a $2.7 million diagnostic testing scam involving the use of unlicensed physicians. Sentencing was scheduled for July.   </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013032201">A Kentucky physician who owned a women's clinic was charged</a> with health care claims fraud, mail fraud, misbranding IUDs and smuggling; if convicted, he could get as much as 233 years in prison and may face a maximum fine of more than $3 million. </li>
<li>In another Kentucky case, <a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013032203">the owner of a drugstore admitted billing</a> Medicare and private insurers for more than $250,000 for fraudulent prescriptions; he was ordered to pay full restitution.  </li>
<li><a href="http://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013040303">A North Carolina woman admitted stealing</a> a therapist's ID and billing Medicaid for $4.8 million for sham mental health services. She also pleaded guilty to conspiracy to launder money, and she admitted trying to sell her nearly $60,000 Mercedes to prevent law enforcement officers from seizing it. She acknowledged using proceeds from the scheme to purchase the car. </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/state/index.asp#SEA2013032501">Two owners of a home health care business</a> in Virginia each were imprisoned for over 10 years and must pay more than $1.8 million for ID theft and false claims. </li>
<li>In another Virginia case, <a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013032202">the president of a rescue squad was convicted</a> of fraudulently billing Medicaid and a private insurer for $2.65 million in an ambulance transport scam. Jailed for four years, the man must pay more than $907,000 dollars in restitution.  </li>
<li><a href="http://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013040302">Two men in Pennsylvania who billed Medicare</a> for more than $2.5 million for ambulance trips for patients who did not need them entered guilty pleas in a fraud case.   </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013041802">A Philadelphia woman pleaded guilty</a> in a $2 million ambulance fraud scheme that involved kickbacks and unneeded or never provided services and false claims.     </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013041801">A Detroit-area office manager was convicted</a> in $5.8 million Medicare scam that included bribery, phony files, and false claims.   </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013032501">A Detroit nurse admitted falsifying</a> patient notes in a massive home health care scam; her actions alone led to fraud of more than $5 million.  </li>
<li>A former Washington, D.C., <a href="http://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013040502">home health care provider admitted falsifying care plans</a> for 62 patients before an OIG Medicare/Medicaid audit.   </li>
<li><a href="http://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013040301">A home health agency owner and a physical therapist</a> in Michigan were convicted in $2.3 million scam involving illegal referrals, kickbacks, fraudulent files and services not rendered. </li>
<li><a href="http://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013040202">The owner and director of nursing of a Louisiana home health agency</a> were convicted in $17.1 million scam  involving paid recruiters, evaluations and other records that were falsified and services that were not medically needed. </li>
<li>In what the U.S. attorney described as "another victory for the good guys," <a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013032205">a Louisiana woman was jailed</a> for 18 months and must pay restitution of more than $129,000 for her part in a $1 million Medicare scam involving wheelchairs and other medical equipment. </li>
<li>Another Louisiana case saw <a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/state/index.asp#SEA2013032001">a former mental health counselor intern charged</a> with submitting false timesheets, leading to alleged false billing of Medicaid. </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/state/index.asp#SEA2013031402">Two defendants were sentenced</a> and another entered a plea of no contest in a Medicaid false claims-theft case in Kansas; more than $25,000 is to be repaid. </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013041601">An Ohio man admitted hiring a woman</a>, who had been excluded as a provider from Federal health care programs, to prepare and submit bills to Medicare and Medicaid. The health care programs were overbilled $2.5 million for services not provided or that were provided by a home health aide with a criminal record who had been excluded from providing health services in people's houses.   </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/state/index.asp#SEA2013032701  (">An Ohio doctor was jailed</a> for five years and must repay Medicaid more than $78,000; the physician billed for more services than he provided and improperly prescribed oxycodone. </li>

</ul>




<div class="contentSeparator"></div>



<h2>From March</h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/oas/reports/region1/11100531.asp">An OIG report</a> found a Connecticut hospital's inpatient rehabilitation documentation was noncompliant. The hospital may owe Medicare nearly $8 million dollars. </li>
<li>OIG found in <a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/oas/reports/region4/41000076.asp">another report</a> that Florida claimed at least $2.2 million dollars in unallowable Medicaid administrative costs. </li>
<li>In yet <a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/oas/reports/region3/31100501.asp">another review</a>, OIG found that a Head Start program in Virginia claimed $949,000 dollars in unallowable grant costs in one year. </li>
<li><a href="http://www.justice.gov/usao/kye/news/2013/2013-02-25-villaspring.html">A Kentucky nursing home and management company</a> reached an agreement with the Federal Government to improve quality of care and will pay $350,000 dollars to settle civil False Claims Act allegations brought in a lawsuit. The settlement agreement is the first of its kind in Kentucky.   </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013022501">A Detroit health care worker</a> was convicted for his part in a $24.7 million dollar Medicare billing scam. He sold patient information that was used in the submission of fraudulent claims. </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013032103">The CEO of a Miami Beach community health center</a> pleaded guilty in a $6 million dollar embezzlement scam.  </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013031504">A pharmacist in Tampa</a> was jailed for 10 years and must repay more than $97,000 dollars for filling hundreds of fraudulent oxycodone prescriptions. Nearly 50,000 pills were later sold on street.   </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013030803">Two medical practices in Corpus Christi, Texas</a>, are to pay $2.3 million dollars to settle allegations of double billing of healthcare programs. </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013031501">A Houston doctor</a> was sent to prison for more than five years and must repay nearly $3 million dollars for falsifying care plans that were used to submit fraudulent bills to Medicare.   </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013030503">A West Virginia physician</a> who owned a pain management practice was jailed for more than 4 years and must pay $6.8 million dollars for fraud and tax evasion. </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013030103">A West Virginia home-care company owner</a> was jailed nearly 4 years for altering and falsifying Medicaid patient records. </li>
<li>In a New York felony case, <a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/state/index.asp#SEA2013031103">a nurse's aide was charged</a> with secretly using his cell phone to take and text a humiliating picture of a nursing home resident. </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013022604">A Manhattan physician</a> was the fourth defendant to plead guilty in an $8.5 million dollar HIV-AIDS clinic scheme. The clinics involved in the scam were described as health care fraud mills. </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/state/index.asp#SEA2013030101">A former oral surgeon</a> who billed Vermont Medicaid for more costly services than he provided was jailed and must repay $50,000. </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/state/index.asp#SEA2013031201">A Milwaukee nurse</a> was convicted of fraud and theft. She billed Medicaid more than $32,000 for 136 days of childcare that she did not provide. </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013031401">An Alabama home health company</a> is to pay $150,000 to resolve allegations that it billed Medicare for ineligible and unneeded services. </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013031503">A Boston rehabilitation hospital</a> settled civil allegations of improper Medicare billing and is  to pay nearly  $92,000. In question was the "midnight rule," which authorizes Medicare reimbursement only when a patient remains in the nursing facility through midnight on a given day.</li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013031302">A Louisiana woman</a> is to pay nearly $73,000 in fines and restitution for filing false daycare services claims.</li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013031402">A counselor in Connecticut</a> admitted filing Medicaid claims for more than $151,000 for hundreds of client sessions that did not occur. </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013031802">A former Department of Health and Services employee</a> will pay restitution after admitting fraud in a retention bonus scheme; he is to be sentenced in June.  </li>
<li>An OIG Most Wanted fugitive, <a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/fugitives/captured_profiles.asp#orisbel">Orisbel Hernandez</a>, accused in a $2.5 million dollar Medicare false claims case, was captured in Miami International Airport. He is charged with health care fraud, mail fraud, aggravated ID theft and making false statements.   </li>
<li></li>
<li>Also captured was <a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/fugitives/captured_profiles.asp#jreyes">Jorge Reyes</a>, indicted in a $9.5 million dollar medical equipment scheme. He was taken into custody in Canada.</li>
<li>Four fugitives, charged with <a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/fugitives/profiles.asp#yousif">bilking Medicaid out of $970,000 dollars</a> in a patient transport scam in Youngstown, Ohio, have been added to OIG's Most Wanted list. They are believed to be in Sudan.</li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/fugitives/profiles.asp#vanounu">Asher Vanounu</a>, charged in an $800,000 dollar medical equipment scam, was also added to the Most Wanted list. He is believed to have fled the country.</li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013030501">Jesse Brown Otter</a> of Minneapolis admitted not paying more than $25,000 dollars in child support; his sentencing is scheduled in May.</li>
</ul>



<div class="contentSeparator"></div>


<h2>From February</h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/state/index.asp#SEA2013020802">A New York psychiatrist</a> was charged in a $230,000 service-claims fraud case; he allegedly wrote prescriptions for what were described as "revolving-door" clients. </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/state/index.asp#SEA2013012901">A Kansas woman</a> was jailed and must repay Medicaid thousands of dollars for fraud, mistreatment of a dependent adult and animal cruelty. </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013020502">A Minnesota woman</a> admitted embezzling $840,000 from the home health company for which she worked and defrauding an insurer of $631,000. </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/state/index.asp#SEA2013021501">The owner of a Florida home care firm</a> was charged with fraud; she is accused of billing Medicaid more than $400,000 for services that were never rendered and billing for services for ineligible recipients. </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/state/index.asp#SEA2013021502">Two Alaska personal care aides</a> were charged with Medicaid fraud; one allegedly submitted bills for services to his dad while working other jobs. </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/state/index.asp#SEA2013021304">Three pleaded guilty in Kentucky</a> to fraud, forgery and theft; they billed Medicaid for services never provided. </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/state/index.asp#SEA2013021401">Eight people in Massachusetts</a> were charged in a $260,000 fraud, including allegedly billing Medicaid for services for someone in jail.  </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013022101">An optometrist in Georgia</a> pleaded guilty in an $800,000 fraud; he billed Medicare for more expensive services than he provided, including claiming that he worked the equivalent of 5&frac12; days in just one day. </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013021401">A Virginia skilled nursing facility</a> is to pay $700,000 to settle allegations that it filed claims for unneeded therapy. </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/state/index.asp#SEA2013020701">Louisiana has sued pharmaceutical giant GlaxoSmithKline</a>, claiming the illegal promotion of nine drugs. - Paxil, Wellbutrin,  Advair,  Lamictal,  Zofran,  Imitrex, Lotronex,  Flovent  and Valtrex. </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/state/index.asp#SEA2013020801">Five dentists and two managers</a> were charged in $5.5 million Medicaid fraud case in New Jersey that, authorities say, involved conspiracy, claims fraud and theft. </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013012501">Four people who ran a community mental health center scam in Florida</a> were sent to prison and must repay Medicare $4.7 million. </li>
<li><a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013021502">The CEO of another community health center in Florida</a> was charged in a multimillion-dollar embezzlement of federal funds. </li>
<li>In a New Jersey case, <a href="https://oig.hhs.gov/fraud/enforcement/criminal/index.asp#CEA2013021501">a cardiologist admitted taking more than $100,000 in cash</a> for illegal patient referrals. The doctor, who has agreed to forfeit the money, is the 10th person to plead guilty in a scheme involving Orange Community MRI, a diagnostic center in Orange, N.J.  </li>
</ul>


<div class="contentSeparator"></div>



<h2>From January</h2>
<ul>
<li>A <a href="http://go.usa.gov/gJVA">regional medical center and a heart center</a> in Ohio have agreed to pay $4.4 million to settle allegations that they submitted claims for unnecessary angioplasty and stent placement procedures on Medicare patients. </li>
<li>Seven defendants in the Orthofix fraud case have been convicted in a $42 million Medicare scam; among them, the former manager of the medical device company was jailed, fined and must forfeit $40,000.  </li>
<li><a href="http://go.usa.gov/4a4R">A Minnesota woman</a>, who worked for a home health care company, was charged with health care fraud and with embezzling $840,000 from her employer. Authorities allege that she double-billed Medicaid and a nonprofit corporation that provides health insurance to families and individuals. </li>
<li><a href="http://go.usa.gov/4KHF">Four people</a> who ran a community mental health center scam in Florida were sent to prison - one for more than five years -- and must repay Medicare $4.7 million. </li>
<li><a href="http://go.usa.gov/4bEj">Seven were charged</a> in a $22 million home health scam in Michigan that allegedly included kickbacks and unneeded and never rendered services.</li>
<li>The <a href="http://go.usa.gov/g7dk">co-owner of a home health care business</a> in suburban Chicago was imprisoned for 10 years and must repay millions in a wide-ranging Medicare fraud scheme that included submitting tens of thousands of false claims.</li>
<li>The manager of a check-cashing store and its anti-money- laundering compliance officer were imprisoned -- one for 5 years, the other for 8 months -- in an $8 million money laundering case in California; fines and forfeitures of $1.2 million were ordered.</li>
<li><a href="http://go.usa.gov/44fk">North Carolina woman</a> who stole a licensed therapist's identification admitted defrauding Medicaid of $8 million for sham mental and behavioral health services. </li>
<li>A <a href="http://go.usa.gov/4bm4">former contract worker</a> in Georgia who routed to her debit cards nearly $9 million that was due providers was jailed for three years for Medicaid fraud. With the help of debit card companies, the Georgia Department of Community Health recovered all but about $17,000, which the defendant was ordered to repay.   </li>
<li>A <a href="http://go.usa.gov/44qA">Michigan podiatrist</a> who submitted fraudulent bills was jailed for more than four years and must pay Medicare and a private insurer more than $1.6 million in restitution. </li>
<li>A <a href="http://go.usa.gov/42Hh">New Jersey pediatrician</a> was charged in a $900,000 wound care scam. Authorities say he billed Medicaid thousands of times, and virtually all of the claims were fraudulent.   According to the complaint against him, the doctor purportedly treated three children 28 times for a total of 49 procedures involving some type of wound repair. The children's mother said that none of the children had ever had a cut that required stitches or other methods of wound closure.</li>
<li><a href="http://go.usa.gov/gHh4">Ten people were charged</a> with taking part in a sophisticated prescription forgery ring in California. </li>
<li>A <a href="http://go.usa.gov/gJpB">physician who fled</a> to Peru and was on the run for 13 years, was jailed for more than 3 years and must pay fines and restitution of $320,000 for health care fraud, mail fraud and failure to appear. He admitted that he had defrauded several insurance companies of over $400,000 and submitted false bills for medical treatment and services that were not provided to his patients.  At the same time, he fraudulently received more than $250,000 in personal disability payments. </li>
</ul>



